Problem of the Day: Find n integers that sum to 0

1/
Weâ€™re asked:
ðŸ‘‰ Given n, build an array of size n
ðŸ‘‰ All numbers must be unique
ðŸ‘‰ Their sum = 0

Sounds like balancing a see-saw ðŸŽ¯. If left has +ve numbers, right must balance with -ve.

2/
Naive thought: Just take pairs like (+1, -1), (+2, -2)â€¦ until we fill n.

Works perfectly for even n.

But odd n leaves one number unpaired ðŸ˜….

So what to do? Add 0! Problem solved âœ….

3/
But in my solution, I did it in one clean math trick ðŸ‘‡

Fill array with 1, 2, 3â€¦ n-1

Then calculate the first element so the whole sum = 0

That formula is:

res[0] = n * (1 - n) / 2;


This ensures total = 0 every time.

4/
ðŸ’» My C++ solution:

vector<int> sumZero(int n) {
    vector<int> res(n);
    res[0] = n * (1 - n) / 2;
    for (int i = 1; i < n; ++i)
        res[i] = i;
    return res;
}


5/
âœ¨ Why this works?

1 + 2 + â€¦ + (n-1) = (n-1)*n/2

So just put the negative of that at index 0.

Balanced! ðŸŽ¯

6/
â±ï¸ Complexity:

Time: O(n) (simple loop)

Space: O(n)

Super efficient and mathy âœ…

7/
ðŸŒ¸ Takeaway:
Sometimes DSA problems are less about heavy logic and more about spotting a neat math pattern.
This one is a perfect example ðŸ’¡

```cpp
  class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> sumZero(int n) {
        vector<int> res(n);
        res[0] = n * (1 - n) / 2;
        for (int i = 1; i < n; ++i)
            res[i] = i;
        return res;
    }
};
```
